[3] Diagnostic mismatches
Date: Thu 6 Oct 2022
Source: medRxiv [edited]
https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2022.08.10.22278644v2


Citation: Wu F, Oghuan J, Gitter A, et al. Wide mismatches in the sequences of primers and probes for Monkeypox virus diagnostic assays. medRxiv. 2022.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Abstract
--------
Rapid and accurate diagnosis of infections is fundamental to containment of disease. Several monkeypox virus (MPV) real-time diagnostic assays have been recommended by the CDC; however, the specificity of the primers and probes in these assays for the ongoing MPV outbreak has not been investigated. We analyzed the primer and probe sequences present in the CDC-recommended monkeypox virus (MPV) generic real-time PCR assay by aligning those sequences against 1730 MPV complete genomes reported in 2022 worldwide. Sequence mismatches were found in 99.08% and 97.46% of genomes for the MPV generic forward and reverse primers, respectively. Mismatch-corrected primers were [synthesized] and compared to the generic assay for MPV detection. Results showed that the 2 primer-template mismatches resulted in an ~11-fold underestimation of initial template DNA in the reaction and a 4-fold increase in the 95% LOD. We further evaluated the specificity of 7 other real-time PCR assays used for MPV and orthopoxvirus (OPV) detection and identified 2 assays with the highest matching score (>99.6%) to the global MPV genome database in 2022. Genetic variations in the primer-probe regions across MPV genomes could indicate the temporal and spatial emergence pattern of monkeypox disease. Our results show that the current MPV real-time generic assay may not be optimal to accurately detect MPV, and the mismatch-corrected assay with full complementarity between primers and current MPV genomes could provide a more sensitive and accurate detection of MPV.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
mjm2020@googlemail.com

[Ideally, diagnostic tests should have a high degree of both sensitivity and specificity. As changes in virus genomes occur over time, diagnostic tests need to be adapted to deal with those changes. Even though genomic changes in DNA viruses such as monkeypox occur more slowly than with RNA viruses, changes do occur. The above report illustrates the need to assess the sensitivity and specificity of tests over time for monkeypox virus diagnosis. - Mod.TY]
